There’s a rhythm to every piece of music… and sometimes, to the way an outfit moves.

This beautiful ensemble from @theindianethnicco theindianethnicco felt like a raag.. graceful, layered, and flowing with emotion. The fabric moved with me, not just on the outside, but within… syncing with my breath, my body, my mood.

Indian ethnic wear, when crafted with soul, becomes more than just clothing.. it becomes expression.
As someone deeply connected to music, styling this piece felt like composing a moment.. where traditional weaves, thoughtful design, and inner stillness came together.

This is why I believe in slow fashion, in choosing clothes that tell stories, that feel like art.
.
.

I’ve always been fond of Indian classical music, dance, and food.. anything that carries a piece of our culture. That’s where my heart truly belongs. And when it comes to clothing, it has to be Indian ethnic wear.

Today, I’m wearing this stunning Mashia Dabu Slub Cotton Hand Embroidered Kali Kurta with churidar, paired with the elegant Pink Droplet Butti Dabu Kota Doriya Dupatta.. both from my favorite, @theindianethnicco 

These are made from pure cotton, and they feel like they’re wrapped in the softness of multiple raagas. Each piece is handcrafted, just like my sitar.. rich with tradition, emotion, and rhythm. The dupatta flows like the taal of water, effortless and poetic.

These are more than clothes.. they are a part of our heritage craft, meant not only to be preserved but also passed on through generations. 

If you haven’t explored @theindianethnicco yet, they create handcrafted, size-inclusive, and culturally rooted Indian wear for women. Each garment is a piece of wearable art, crafted with love and care.

If you’re looking to experience the magic of slow fashion, sustainable clothing, and Indian textiles, do check out their Instagram page and website. Trust me, it’s a world worth stepping into. 
.
Outfit:- @theindianethnicco

latestPosts.caption:
I’ve always been deeply fascinated by the history of the world.. especially ancient civilizations and their artistic expressions. Just a few days ago, my husband and I were talking about the art of the Harappan period and how beautiful it would be to bring that heritage into our home decor. And as if the universe was listening, I received a message from @studiovirasat a brand that creates stunning Harappan terracotta seals for homes that carry stories, culture, and history within their walls. 

You know The seals of the Indus Valley Civilization were small, hand-carved artifacts made from terracotta or steatite, used for trade, identity, or ritual purposes. Each seal tells a story through symbols, script, and animal motifs.. When the package arrived, I was in awe. These handcrafted pieces are so intricately detailed and thoughtfully made. Let me introduce you to the seals I received:

Pashupati Seal
A meditative figure surrounded by animals.. often linked to early yogic traditions. It reflects harmony, power, and the bond between humans and nature.

Zebu Bull Seal
An iconic image of a large-horned bull.. believed to symbolize strength, stability, and the spirit of trade and prosperity.

Pipal Leaf Seal
Inspired by the sacred pipal tree, it speaks of reverence, ritual, and the deep-rooted connection between nature and spirituality.

Three-Headed Herbivore Seal
A lesser-known but striking motif of a mythical creature.. showcasing the imagination, symbolism, and layered storytelling of Harappan design. I definitely recommend checking out @studiovirasat These pieces are not just decor.. they are timeless fragments of ancient India brought back to life.
.

Some pieces aren’t worn.. they are lived, felt, remembered. This Ajrakh Anarkali and Jamdani two-piece set from @suru.chira are more than just clothes.. they are a tribute to India’s rich textile heritage.
Ajrakh, with its deep natural tones and intricate mirror work, echoes the landscapes of Gujarat… while the Jamdani flows in soft green layers, handwoven with quiet care.. like stories passed down through generations.
Suruchira has turned these ancient arts into silhouettes that feel at home in today’s world.. elegant, easy to wear, and full of meaning.

I’m so happy to share these with you.. a little moment of stillness, craft, and connection in a fast world.
.
Ajrakh and Jamdani outfits :- @suru.chira

latestPosts.caption:
I recently received this stunning Ivory Chikankari Dupatta from @utsav_by_sahajnidhi , and I’m completely in love with it. The intricate Chikankari embroidery is an authentic, handmade craft by skilled local artisans from Lucknow.. thoughtfully done all over the fabric, making it truly exquisite.

Dupattas are the soul of Indian ethnic wear.. whether it’s a salwar suit or a kurta set.. and when they carry such rich cultural heritage, they deserve to be celebrated. This timeless ivory beauty isn’t just limited to traditional styling. You can drape it over jeans and a short kurti or even mix it with Indo-Western outfits for a contemporary twist.

I styled it the classic way.. a black and white look featuring a solid black co-ord set, paired with green glass bangles, matching green earrings, vibrant red alta on my palms, and a gajra to complete the Banno Rani vibe. It felt festive, traditional, and so close to my roots.. and I loved every bit of it.

If you’re looking to add handcrafted elegance to your wardrobe, do check out @utsav_by_sahajnidhi for more beautiful, artisanal pieces.
.
Chikankari Dupatta :- @utsav_by_sahajnidhi 
Earrings:- @hiranya.store 
Black Co ord set :- @lugdabydihi

Art on your wall? Beautiful. But art on your skin, moving as you breathe, turning corners with you, catching morning light or chai steam? That’s something else entirely.

This shirt by @naymish featuring Raja Ravi Varma’s Shakuntala isn’t just a piece of clothing. It’s a reminder of how powerful stories are.. especially when women carry them.

Designed in soft, airy cotton that feels like second skin, tailored to fall gently but clean, and printed with a timeless painting that’s now part of your everyday world.

You don’t wear this shirt. You live in it. To work meetings and walks, To art fairs, poetry nights, or just watering plants in silence. With pants or skirts, tucked in or left flowing, with kolhapuris or boots. Style it your way. And let the story change with you.

Which version of you will wear it next? . Shirt Shakuntala by Raja Ravi Varma :- @naymish  . .

This is Shakuntala, reimagined.. not in a frame, but in motion. @naymish takes Raja Ravi Varma’s iconic painting and brings it into a world where women are many things.. professionals, dreamers, artists, mothers, rebels, lovers.

The soft cotton moves with your body, not against it. The subtle tailored structure gives form, but never limits. And the print? It speaks.. softly, but clearly.
Style it with trousers for work, layer it with a vest and boots for an art show, or wear it loose on a Sunday morning with coffee and a messy bun.
It doesn’t just fit your routine.. it fits your rhythm. . Shirt Shakuntala by Raja Ravi Varma :- @naymish  . .

Draped in the Honey Dew Top and Cypress Sway Pants by @shopchao.in , made from the softest linen, I moved through the hours with calm intention. The flowing forms and grounded tones echoed the rhythm around me.. gentle, steady, and true.

As twilight approached, I slipped into the Misty Meadow Dress. Feather-light in airy organza, it drifted with each step, catching the last golden light like a tender whisper. There was grace in its simplicity.. where elegance met ease, and fabric turned into feeling.

I paired it with the linen Cypress Sway Pants once more, layering textures and moods. A minimal yet bold necklace grounded the look, while my mother’s 40-year-old clutch added a quiet, storied touch.. a memory held in hand.

There’s a rare comfort in wearing pieces that don’t just adorn, but align.. with your pace, your breath, your way of being. Serene. Fluid. Free..
